18. 4Sum
Idea

4Sum is an extension of 3Sum.

In 3Sum:

Fix 1 element
Use two pointers for remaining 2 elements

In 4Sum:

Fix 2 elements
Use two pointers for remaining 2 elements
Approach
Sort the array
Use first loop for first element
Use second loop for second element
Use two pointers:
left
right
Find quadruplets whose sum equals target
Skip duplicates
Why Sorting?

Sorting helps:

move left pointer to increase sum
move right pointer to decrease sum
avoid duplicates easily
Java Optimal Solution
class Solution {

    public List<List<Integer>> fourSum(int[] nums, int target) {

        List<List<Integer>> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        int n = nums.length;

        for (int i = 0; i < n - 3; i++) {

            // Skip duplicate first elements
            if (i > 0 && nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) {
                continue;
            }

            for (int j = i + 1; j < n - 2; j++) {

                // Skip duplicate second elements
                if (j > i + 1 && nums[j] == nums[j - 1]) {
                    continue;
                }

                int left = j + 1;
                int right = n - 1;

                while (left < right) {

                    long sum =
                        (long) nums[i] +
                        nums[j] +
                        nums[left] +
                        nums[right];

                    // Quadruplet found
                    if (sum == target) {

                        ans.add(Arrays.asList(
                            nums[i],
                            nums[j],
                            nums[left],
                            nums[right]
                        ));

                        left++;
                        right--;

                        // Skip duplicate left values
                        while (left < right &&
                               nums[left] == nums[left - 1]) {
                            left++;
                        }

                        // Skip duplicate right values
                        while (left < right &&
                               nums[right] == nums[right + 1]) {
                            right--;
                        }
                    }

                    // Need bigger sum
                    else if (sum < target) {
                        left++;
                    }

                    // Need smaller sum
                    else {
                        right--;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Why Use long?
long sum

Important because integer overflow can happen.

Example:

1000000000 + 1000000000 + ...

may exceed int range.

Dry Run
Input
nums = [1,0,-1,0,-2,2]
target = 0

After sorting:

[-2,-1,0,0,1,2]
i = 0
nums[i] = -2
j = 1
nums[j] = -1

left = 2

right = 5

Sum:

-2 + (-1) + 0 + 2 = -1

Need bigger sum → move left.

Next:

-2 + (-1) + 1 + 2 = 0

Quadruplet:

[-2,-1,1,2]
Output
[
 [-2,-1,1,2],
 [-2,0,0,2],
 [-1,0,0,1]
]
Time Complexity
O(n³)
Two loops
One two-pointer traversal
Space Complexity
O(1)

